The Asian Development Bank warned of a potential epidemic in China due to tainted food affecting over 300 million people annually.
The lack of food safety laws and supervision poses a threat to public health and the economy.
The government has initiated a food safety evaluation campaign in major cities to address these concerns.
Calls for a unified supervision mechanism and stricter punishments for offenders have been made to prevent future food safety scares.
With food and drug safety becoming a top priority, China aims to enhance monitoring and enforcement to ensure the safety of its food products.
